origination.label: Creator

did.abstract: The collection consists of the administrative papers from the tenure of Henry H. Remak, who served as director or the Institute for Advanced Study from 1988-1994 and interim director from 1997-1998.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Select files closed to researchers. Advance notice is required.

bioghist.head: Administrative History
bioghist.p: The Institute for Advanced Study was founded in 1981 with the goal of bringing distinguished lecturers and visitors from all over the world to Bloomington in order to pursue thier research and collaborate with IU faculty and studnets.As such, IAS hosts a variety of seminars, lectures and working groups featuring scientists, artists, and scholars from around the world.

Noteworthy alumni of the Institute include composer and conductor Leonard Bernstein; author, historian and semiotician Umberto Eco; author Ursula K. LeGuin; former President of Singapore C. V. Devan Nair; and Nobel laureate Chen Ning Yang; to name a few.

In addition to supporting scholars from outside the IU community through Visiting Fellowships and Branigan Lectureships, the IAS also offers funding opportunities to IU faculty through the Remak Distinguished Scholar Award and Mini-Workshop/Conference Grants.

IAS is supported by the Society for Advanced Study – a group of more than 100 members who strive to communicate the Institute's goals to the broader campus and Bloomington communities. The Society supports the Institute financially, as well.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is organized in a single series of Administrative files, arranged alphabetically by folder heading.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: Arranged alphabetically by folder heading, the bulk of the collection consists of correspondence between Institute for Advanced Studies Director Henry Remak and a prolific range of noteworthy fellows and visiting scholars whom Remak helped to attract to Indiana University. Among them include world-renowned semiotician, historian, and fiction author – Umberto Eco; two-time nominee for the Nobel Peace Prize and spokeswoman for the Chinese Democracy Movement – Chai Ling; leading European chemist – Lord Lewis of Newnham; and winner of the prestigious Lenin Prize in Physics – Sergei Denisov. Also included are correspondence between Remak and his colleagues and assistants at the Institute and a small amount of other administrative files of the Institute such as annual reports.

Restricted files are listed where they would fall in the intellectual organization of the collection but are physically located at the end of Box 7 and in Box 8. Files marked as restricted typically contain letters of recommendation and evaluation or other such personnel items and thus, are closed. Researchers interested in viewing these files should contact the IU Archives well in advance of their visit to allow time to review the files and remove restricted items.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material
relatedmaterial.p: Additional records such as newsletters, annual reports, bulletins, and publications may be accessed in the Archives of Institutional Memory
